    return response_text, figure

Return Type:
tuple[str, matplotlib.figure.Figure | None]


That means:

The first element â†’ string (your text answer)

The second element â†’ Matplotlib Figure or None (if no chart)

âœ… Summary

Function	Return Type	Description
fetch_weather()	`dict	None`
.json() method	dict	Converts JSON to dictionary
generate_weather_response()	`tuple[str, Figure	None]`

me: what is https in api response?
ai: Great question! When you see https:// in an API request or response, it means the communication is happening over the HTTPS protocol (Hypertext Transfer Protocol Secure) rather than plain HTTP. Hereâ€™s what that means and why it matters:

ğŸ” What is HTTPS?

HTTPS is essentially HTTP wrapped inside a security layer â€” specifically, it uses encryption (via TLS/SSL) for the data transmitted between client and server. 
Wikipedia
+3
GeeksforGeeks
+3
GeeksforGeeks
+3

It ensures three key things:

Confidentiality: The data canâ€™t easily be read by someone intercepting the network. 
educative.io
+1

Integrity: The data arriving has not been tampered with in transit. 
educative.io

Authentication: The server youâ€™re talking to is (ideally) the one you think it is. 
upguard.com
+1

âœ… Why it matters for APIs

Since APIs often exchange sensitive or private data (e.g., weather data might not be too sensitive, but other APIs might return user data, financial info, etc.), using HTTPS helps protect that data from being intercepted.

Many modern APIs require HTTPS â€” HTTP (without the â€œSâ€) is often considered insecure or deprecated. 
MoldStud

When you call an API using https://, youâ€™re ensuring the request and response are inside a secure tunnel rather than plaintext.

ğŸ§© What youâ€™ll see in responses

When you make an API call over HTTPS:

The URL will start with https://

The HTTP status line (e.g., 200 OK) and headers will be part of the response just like normal HTTP. 
getstream.io
+1

The body (data content) is the same format youâ€™d get with HTTP â€” e.g., JSON or XML â€” but it arrives over an encrypted channel.

From your codeâ€™s viewpoint (e.g., using requests.get("https://...") in Python), you wonâ€™t usually see the encryption layer; it happens under the hood.

â— Common misunderstanding

Some people think â€œHTTPSâ€ changes the data format or response structure of an API â€” it doesnâ€™t. It only changes how the data is transported (securely). The JSON body, headers, etc., are unaffected by the difference between HTTP and HTTPS.
